entry.title: [GridNG] Omit `auto` sizes for `grid-template-*` serialization
entry.content:
Per https://drafts.csswg.org/cssom/#serializing-css-values "If component values can be omitted or replaced with a shorter representation without changing the meaning of the value, omit/replace them."



This means that when serializing `grid-template-*`, we should always omit `auto` sizes in `grid-template-*` serialization as it is the

default value, so it will always be a shorter representation

without changing the value. This should happen regardless of whether

it was specified by the author.



This also means that the final test case expectation in

grid-template-shorthand-valid.html is incorrect, which lead me all over the place on early iterations of this CL. The above

CSSWG quote and the fact that Safari and Firefox fail for the same

reason has me confident that the assertion there is incorrect. I

will update the test to the correct behavior in a follow-up CL.

entry.title: Choose closest covering position for large snap areas
entry.content:
This patch modifies the logic to find snap positions so that when a scroller is scrolled to a position which only partially covers a snap

area larger than itself, if it snaps to this large snap area, it snaps

to the nearest boundary of that snap area where the snap area covers the

snap port, rather than doing a jump to honor the specified scroll-snap-align.



Below are a few notes about changes made to tests:



snap-area-overflow-boundary.html is corrected so that both test cases

correctly verify the scroll offset when snapped to the lower element.

The scroll amount in the second test case is also adjusted to ensure

it is enough to snap to the lower div.



The expectations at the end of

scroll-on-large-element-not-covering-snapport.tentative.html are

updated to account for choosing a snap position different from the

scroll-snap-align-specified position for snap areas larger than their

snapports.



scroll-snap-type-on-root-element.html is updated to account for

scrollbar width since snapping to the right edge of the target is

valid.



This patch picks new programmatic scroll offsets for

snap-to-visible-areas-margin-both.html so that the top-left of

intersection of the right-top and left-bottom targets' scroll-margins

is closer than the bottom-right of the intersection.



scrollend-with-snap-on-fractional-offset.html and

scroll-start-with-scroll-snap-tentative.html are adjusted to use snap

area sizes that don't cover the snap port.

entry.title: Check http protocol when emitting resource timing entry
entry.content:
Currently when a resource load via file protocol fails, a resource

timing is emitted. We should only emit resource timing for resources

that are fetched over http(s) protocols or from web bundles.



This CL is to fix this issue. The ResourceResponse::ShouldPopulateResourceTiming() method used for

checking protocol when load is successful checks if the

ResourceResponse::current_request_url_ is HTTP or the web bundle url

is valid.



However when the load fails, the ResourceResponse::current_request_url_

could be null, so we use ResourceRequest::url_, since we are only

checking for protocols.

entry.title: [AFP] Implement NetworkServiceResourceBlockList
entry.content:
This block list works by evaluating the request and the top frame URLs

in a manner similar to NetworkServiceProxyAllowList. If the resource URL

is in the block list, the request will only be blocked if the top frame

is not first party based on the allowed domains in the block list. At

this time, the block list and first party relationships are provided by

Masked Domain List (blocked resources have additional metadata to

distinguish them) but will be populated with data from a different

Chrome component in the future.



This also moves the MDL-based NetworkServiceProxyAllowList to the new

services/network/masked_domain_list directory.

entry.content:
This CL adds a ToVkFormatExternalSampler() function for clients to use

when receiving SIF instances with external sampling. Nothing in the

codebase yet uses this, but we will be augmenting callsites of

ToVkFormat() in anticipation of using multiplanar SI for hardware video

ToVkFormat() for the same reasons as used for ToGLFormatDesc(): As

clients in general need to handle multiplanar with external sampling

differently than multiplanar with per-plane sampling, we want to force

awareness of which type of sampling is being used on the caller side.

entry.title: Fix slowness when updating or clearing sync metadata for passwords
entry.content:
HasUnsyncedPasswordDeletions() can be slow for users with many passwords

and invoking it for each change (update or clearing) can lead to

quadratic runtime complexity in certain prominent scenarios such as

sign-in or turning sync on.



Instead, most calls can be optimized away by instead issuing individual

lookups for sync entity metadata. After all, the relevant scenario for

the SyncMetadataStore::UpdateEntityMetadata() codepath (e.g. used during

sign-in or turn-sync-on) is extremely unlikely and can be optimized away

in practically all cases (it's only relevant for conflict-resolution).



The optimization for SyncMetadataStore::ClearEntityMetadata() isn't

known to impact very common cases, but for example improves performance

for users with a large number of passwords that issue deletions for a

moderately-large fraction (not all).

entry.content:
Two different warnings in `_GenerateStubsAndAssert()` get swallowed up

when building from a TTY. This is not a problem in CI, since ninja

appears not to clobber the newline-less emission when the output is not

a TTY. However, when run "interactively," ninja's status line will mask

the output from this function, making the warning message illegible.



To fix, we simply emit a newline at the end of the message.



This CL also trivially adjusts the function so not to join more content

to `warning_message`, writing it straight to `sys.stderr`.

entry.title: in_process_fuzzer: timeout avoidance
entry.content:
in_process_fuzzer is a framework to run fuzz cases within an entire

browser_test instance. Such complex fuzz cases are rarely running a

simple algorithm, but often intentionally invoke complex browser

functionality which might take an arbitrary, or infinite, time to run.



Currently such fuzzers therefore suffer from crashes when their nested

run loops expire.



This CL adds a facility by which such fuzzers can declare that they've

found an infinitely-running fuzz case. When running using centipede,

this will cause the browser to exit - the centipede runner will then

restart the browser with further fuzz cases - thus successfully

discarding the infinitely-running input.



This facility isn't used by any fuzzers in this CL, but it's in use in

some experimental CLs and seems to work well. Comments document how it

should be used.

should be working properly, it has been decided to create a separate

flag to be able to turn off the feature in case of unintended behavior.

entry.title: SafeBrowsingSyncObserver: Migrate away from IsSyncFeatureEnabled()
entry.content:
Background: The concept of Sync-the-feature is going away, see

go/uno-umbrella for more background. Once that launches,

IsSyncFeatureEnabled() will always return false (and will eventually

be removed entirely).



SafeBrowsingSyncObserver is used to observe changes to "the Sync state",

which trigger the clearing of some caches.

Instead of the to-be-deprecated IsSyncFeatureEnabled(), this CL updates

the observer to check for changes to the user's opt-in to sync history

data specifically, which in a way is the closest equivalent in the new

world.

Specifically, for syncing users, it's almost equivalent - a cache clear

will now also be triggered when the user turns on/off the "History"

toggle in sync settings, which (a) seems reasonable and (b) is rare.
